{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486710","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486710"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:42:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:42:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"160"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"160","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/160"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.24,0.12,0.49,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"160"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77174"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"160","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/160"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"160"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62682"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1086"},{"type":"tags","id":"2132"},{"type":"tags","id":"2142"},{"type":"tags","id":"2956"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"9736"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2633"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35638"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42008"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42974"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77174","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77174"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 70-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-week history of frothy urine. He has a medical history of type 2 diabetes mellitus diagnosed 20 years ago, managed with metformin and gliclazide. He does not take any other regular medications. He denies shortness of breath, cough, fever or rashes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is bilateral pitting oedema to the mid-shins. The remainder of the examination is unremarkable. Urinalysis shows 3+ protein. Blood tests reveal deteriorating renal function with serum creatinine 180 \u03bcmol/L (60-110) and albumin 28 g/L (35-50). A renal biopsy is performed.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most likely to be present on renal biopsy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Extensive glomerular crescents","Hyaline arteriolosclerosis","Diffuse capillary wall thickening with immune complex deposits","Kimmelstiel-Wilson nodules","IgA deposition in glomerular mesangium"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features of nephrotic syndrome (proteinuria, hypoalbuminaemia, peripheral oedema) in the context of long-standing type 2 diabetes mellitus. The most likely diagnosis is diabetic nephropathy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKimmelstiel-Wilson nodules\u003C/strong\u003E are pathognomonic for advanced diabetic nephropathy. These nodular lesions typically develop after 10-15 years of diabetes and represent areas of mesangial expansion with matrix accumulation. They are often accompanied by diffuse glomerular basement membrane thickening.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHyaline arteriolosclerosis\u003C/strong\u003E is characteristic of hypertensive nephropathy, though it can also be seen as a secondary finding in diabetic nephropathy. It represents hyaline deposition in arteriolar walls but is not specific enough to confirm diabetic nephropathy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiffuse capillary wall thickening with immune complex deposits\u003C/strong\u003E is the hallmark of membranous nephropathy. While this can cause nephrotic syndrome in older adults, the presence of long-standing diabetes makes diabetic nephropathy more likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExtensive glomerular crescents\u003C/strong\u003E are seen in rapidly progressive glomerulonephritis, including anti-glomerular basement membrane disease and ANCA-associated vasculitis. The gradual onset and absence of other systemic symptoms make these conditions unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIgA deposition in glomerular mesangium\u003C/strong\u003E is diagnostic of IgA nephropathy, which typically presents with episodes of visible haematuria rather than nephrotic syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Kimmelstiel-Wilson nodules are pathognomonic for advanced diabetic nephropathy on renal biopsy.","Nephrotic syndrome is characterised by proteinuria, hypoalbuminaemia, peripheral oedema and hyperlipidaemia.","Long-standing diabetes (\u003E10 years) is a major risk factor for developing diabetic nephropathy."],"references":["Alsaad KO, Herzenberg AM. Distinguishing diabetic nephropathy from other causes of glomerulosclerosis: an update. J Clin Pathol. 2007;60(1):18-26. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/17213346/","Kodner C. Diagnosis and Management of Nephrotic Syndrome in Adults. Am Fam Physician. 2016 Mar 15;93(6):479-85. PMID: 26977832. Available at: https://www.aafp.org/pubs/afp/issues/2016/0315/p479.html","Couser WG. Rapidly progressive glomerulonephritis: classification, pathogenetic mechanisms, and therapy. Am J Kidney Dis. 1988 Jun;11(6):449-64. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/3287904/","Foggensteiner L, Mulroy S, Firth J. Management of diabetic nephropathy. J R Soc Med. 2001;94(5):210-217. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/11385086/","Kimmelstiel P, Wilson C. Intercapillary Lesions in the Glomeruli of the Kidney. Am J Pathol. 1936 Jan;12(1):83-98.7. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC1911022/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62682"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"160"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62682","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62682"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-06T11:06:21+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-10T09:03:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"160"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77174"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"In